Went to the Summerlin location for one of their pre-official-opening lunches, and ordered:  + Thai Peanut Chicken Sandwich + Roasted Red Pepper Lobster Bisque + Asiago Croutons (for the soup) + Caramel Brownie  The high ceilings of the dining area make it seem larger than it is at first glance, but either the crowds or the table organization made it feel somewhat cramped.
The Recharge Bar did not look like it was working yet.
Typical orders consist of a soup, salad, sandwich, or their "Pick 2" combo.
The Pick 2 combo affords you 2 of the following: 1 whole sandwich, 1/2 salad, or 1/2 soup.
As you walk down the order counter, you can see their selection of salad, sandwich, and soup ingredients if you want to customize an existing order or make one from scratch.
At the end of the counter is a very nice dessert rack filled with several types of creme brulee, cheesecake, and brownies.
The staff was on the ball, and the speed of the line was dictated by the people ordering, not the people fulfilling the orders.
The food was all delicious.
The sandwich bread is a bit big, but the Thai chicken salad was sweet and flavorful, with strong peanut and greens (cilantro?
) flavor.
I loved the red pepper lobster bisque.
The bisque hosted a small amount of shredded lobster, and the red pepper imparted a bit of spice to the soup.
Quite hearty.
The asiago croutons were somewhat bland and not really necessary for the soup; they're an optional add-on, so I'd say you probably don't need them unless you're a big fan of croutons.
The caramel brownie was very sweet, very rich, and very heavy.
Then again, when you order a caramel brownie that's pretty much what you'd expect, so they've succeeded there.
Overall, Cafe Zupas is well worth visiting for the nice variety of tasty food.
I definitely will be back to try out some of the other selections here.

